</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Board completed its annual review of non-employee director compensation in December 2014 and determined that no
changes to any of the compensation elements were warranted for 2015. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Payment of Annual Retainer and Committee Chair Fees </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-bottom:0px; "><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The annual retainer and any applicable committee chair fees for all non-employee directors are paid in quarterly installments on the
15</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th </SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">day of March, June, September and December, or the
prior business day if the 15</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> is not a business day.
Non-employee directors may elect to receive all or a portion of the annual retainer in cash or in Common Stock. Non-employee directors may also elect to defer receipt of all or a portion of the retainer or committee chair fees until the date their
membership on the Board ends. Committee chair fees that are not deferred are paid only in cash. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">28 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Non-employee directors choosing to defer all or a portion of their retainer or committee chair fees may
invest the deferred amounts in two ways: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In a cash account that values the performance of the investment based upon the performance of one or more third-party investment funds selected by the
director from among the mutual funds or other investment options available to all employees participating in our 401(k) Plan. Amounts invested in the cash account are paid only in cash. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In a deferred common stock unit account that we value according to the performance of our Common Stock, including reinvested dividends. Amounts
invested in the deferred common stock unit account are paid in shares of Common Stock. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Restricted Stock Units
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-bottom:0px; "><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">RSUs are granted quarterly to non-employee directors on the first day of January, April, July and October. In 2014,
the number of RSUs granted in each quarter was determined by dividing $33,750 by the average closing price of a share of our Common Stock on the New York Stock Exchange (&#147;NYSE&#148;) on the last three trading days preceding the grant date. RSUs
awarded to non-employee directors vest one year after the date of grant, or earlier upon termination of the director&#146;s membership on the Board by reason of retirement (termination of service from the Board after the director&#146;s 60</FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> birthday), death or disability, for any reason after a Change in
Control as defined in our Executive Benefits Protection Plan (Group 3A) (&#147;EBPP 3A&#148;), or under such other circumstances as the Board may determine. Vested RSUs are payable to directors in shares of Common Stock or, at the option of the
director, can be deferred as common stock units under the Directors&#146; Compensation Plan until the director&#146;s membership on the Board ends. Dividend equivalent units are credited at regular rates on the RSUs during the restriction period
and, upon vesting of the RSUs, are payable in shares of Common Stock or deferred as common stock units together with any RSUs the director has deferred. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As of February&nbsp;27, 2015, Messrs. Davis, Malcolm, Mead, Nevels, Ridge, Shedlarz and Ms.&nbsp;Arway had attained retirement age for purposes of the vesting of RSUs. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Other Compensation, Reimbursements and Programs </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Board occasionally establishes committees of limited duration for special purposes. The Board will consider paying additional compensation to non-employee directors who serve on special committees,
generally $1,250 per meeting, if the special committee holds six or more meetings, each lasting one hour or more. No director received compensation for service on a special committee in 2014. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We reimburse our directors for travel and other out-of-pocket expenses they incur when attending Board and committee meetings and for minor incidental expenses they incur when performing directors&#146;
services. We also provide reimbursement for at least one director continuing education program each year. Directors receive travel accident insurance while traveling on the Company&#146;s business and receive discounts on the purchase of our
products to the same extent and on the same terms as our employees. Directors also are eligible to participate in the Company&#146;s Gift Matching Program. Under the Gift Matching Program, the Company will match, upon a director&#146;s request,
contributions made by the director to one or more charitable organizations, on a dollar-for-dollar basis up to a maximum aggregate contribution of $5,000 annually. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">29 </FONT></P>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">*</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Director </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Information Regarding Our
Controlling Stockholder </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In 1909, Milton S. and Catherine S. Hershey established a trust having as its sole beneficiary Milton Hershey
School, a non-profit school for the full-time care and education of disadvantaged children located in Hershey, Pennsylvania. Hershey Trust Company, a state-chartered trust company, is trustee of the Milton Hershey School Trust. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In its capacity as trustee for the Milton Hershey School Trust, Hershey Trust Company is our controlling stockholder. In this capacity, it will have the
right to cast 7.9% of all of the votes entitled to be cast on matters requiring the vote of the Common Stock voting separately and 80.9% of all of the votes entitled to be cast on matters requiring the vote of the Common Stock and Class B Common
Stock voting together. The board of directors of Hershey Trust Company, with the approval of the board of managers (governing body) of Milton Hershey School, decides how funds held by Hershey Trust Company, as trustee for the Milton Hershey School
Trust, will be invested. The board of directors of Hershey Trust Company generally decides how shares of The Hershey Company held by Hershey Trust Company, as trustee for the Milton Hershey School Trust, will be voted. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As of the Record Date, Hershey Trust Company also held 389,000 shares of our Common Stock as investments. The board of directors or management of Hershey
Trust Company decides how these shares will be voted. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">34 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In all, Hershey Trust Company, as trustee for the Milton Hershey School Trust and as direct owner of
investment shares, will be entitled to vote 12,902,821 shares of our Common Stock and 60,612,012 shares of our Class B Common Stock at the Annual Meeting. Stated in terms of voting power, Hershey Trust Company will have the right to cast 8.1% of all
of the votes entitled to be cast on matters requiring the vote of the Common Stock voting separately and 80.9% of all of the votes entitled to be cast on matters requiring the vote of the Common Stock and Class B Common Stock voting together at the
Annual Meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our certificate of incorporation contains the following important provisions regarding our Class B Common Stock: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">All holders of Class B Common Stock, including Hershey Trust Company, as trustee for Milton Hershey School, may convert any of their Class B Common
Stock shares into shares of our Common Stock at any time on a share-for-share basis. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">All shares of Class B Common Stock will automatically be converted to shares of Common Stock on a share-for-share basis if Hershey Trust Company, as
trustee for Milton Hershey School, or any successor trustee, or Milton Hershey School, as appropriate, ceases to hold more than 50% of the total Class B Common Stock shares outstanding and at least 15% of the total Common Stock and Class B Common
Stock shares outstanding. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We must obtain the approval of Hershey Trust Company, as trustee for Milton Hershey School, or any successor trustee, or Milton Hershey School, as
appropriate, before we issue any Common Stock or take any other action that would deprive Hershey Trust Company, as trustee for Milton Hershey School, or any successor trustee, or Milton Hershey School, as appropriate, of the ability to cast a
majority of the votes on any matter where the Class B Common Stock is entitled to vote, either separately as a class or together with any other class. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">35 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="4"><B><A NAME="toc791430_16"></A>AUDIT COMMITTEE REPORT </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>To Our Stockholders: </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Audit Committee
is currently comprised of four directors, each of whom is considered independent under the NYSE Rules and the rules and regulations of the SEC. The Board has determined that each member of the Audit Committee is financially literate and that each of
Messrs. Davis, Mead and Nevels qualifies as an &#147;audit committee financial expert,&#148; as that term is defined under the rules promulgated by the SEC. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our role as the Audit Committee is to assist the Board in its oversight of: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>

<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Audit Committee operates under a written charter that was last reviewed by the Audit Committee on December&nbsp;8, 2014. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our duties as an Audit Committee include overseeing the Company&#146;s management, internal auditors and independent auditors in their performance of the
following functions, for which they are responsible: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Management </FONT></P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Discussed with the independent auditors their independence from the Company. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We are not employees of the Company and are not performing the functions of auditors or accountants. We are not responsible as an Audit Committee or individually to conduct &#147;field work&#148; or other
types of auditing or accounting reviews or procedures or to set auditor independence standards. In carrying out our duties as Audit Committee members, we have relied on the information provided to us by management and the independent auditors.
Consequently, we do not assure that the audit of the Company&#146;s financial statements has been carried out in accordance with generally accepted auditing standards, that the financial statements are presented in accordance with U.S. generally
accepted accounting principles or that the Company&#146;s auditors are in fact &#147;independent.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Based on the reports and discussions
described in this report, and subject to the limitations on our role and responsibilities as an Audit Committee referred to above and in our charter, we recommended to the Board that the audited financial statements be included in the Company&#146;s
Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014, filed with the SEC on February&nbsp;20, 2015. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P><DIV ALIGN="right">

to delegate to one or more of its members the authority to pre-approve any audit, audit-related or non-audit services, provided that the approval is presented to the Audit Committee at its next scheduled meeting. </FONT></P>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="4"><B><A NAME="toc791430_18"></A>PROPOSAL NO. 2 &#150; RATIFICATION OF APPOINTMENT
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="4"><B>OF INDEPENDENT AUDITORS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Audit Committee has appointed KPMG LLP as the Company&#146;s independent auditors for 2015. Although not required to do so, the Board, upon the Audit Committee&#146;s recommendation, has determined to
submit the Audit Committee&#146;s appointment of KPMG LLP as our independent auditors to stockholders for ratification as a matter of good corporate governance. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Audit Committee&#146;s appointment of KPMG LLP as the Company&#146;s independent auditors for 2015 will be considered ratified if a majority of the shares of the Common Stock and Class B Common Stock
(voting together without regard to class) present and entitled to vote at the Annual Meeting are voted for the proposal. If stockholders do not ratify the appointment of KPMG LLP as the Company&#146;s independent auditors for 2015, the Audit
Committee will reconsider its appointment. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Representatives of KPMG&nbsp;LLP will attend the Annual Meeting, will have the opportunity to make
a statement, if they so desire, and will respond to questions. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="97%"></TD></TR>


<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px; padding-right:8px"> <P STYLE="font-size:10px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Board of Directors unanimously recommends that stockholders vote <B>FOR</B> ratification of&nbsp;the Audit Committee&#146;s appointment of KPMG LLP as the Company&#146;s independent auditors for
2015.</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:16px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px" align="left"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD></TR>

 <div style="width:100%;margin-left:0%; margin-right:0%;background-color:#3f000b;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:3px"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:1%;margin-right:1%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="6"></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="6" COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="6" COLOR="#ffffff"><A NAME="toc791430_19"></A>Compensation Discussion &amp;
Analysis </FONT></B></FONT></P></div> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="4"><B><A NAME="toc791430_20"></A>EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">This section discusses and analyzes the decisions we made concerning the compensation of our named executive officers (&#147;NEOs&#148;) for 2014. It also
describes the process for determining executive compensation and the factors considered in determining the amount of compensation awarded to our NEOs. The NEOs for 2014 are: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="line-height:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:1pt solid #000000;width:21%">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">(1)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Mr.&nbsp;Tacka retired effective December&nbsp;31, 2014. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Executive Summary </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>2014 Highlights </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The story of The Hershey Company (the &#147;Company&#148;) spans nearly a century and a half of industrial and social change. Today, the Company is a
global confectionary company with a footprint that includes many countries and cultures around the world. With over 80 brands driving over $7.4 billion in annual revenues, we are focused on growing our presence in key international markets while
continuing to build our competitive advantage in North America. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In January 2014, we announced high expectations for the Company, incorporating
these goals into our 2014 incentive programs: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Volume-driven, full-year 2014 net sales to increase 5% to 7% from 2013; and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">2014 adjusted earnings per share-diluted to increase 9% to 11% from 2013. We define adjusted earnings per share-diluted as diluted earnings per share
of the Company&#146;s common stock (&#147;Common Stock&#148;), excluding adjustments as described beginning on page&nbsp;18 of the 2014 Annual Report on Form 10-K that accompanies this Proxy Statement. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">40 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">While we did not meet our high expectations, Hershey delivered industry-leading growth in both net sales and
adjusted earnings per share-diluted. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center">


<IMG SRC="g791430g82g10.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Despite the Company delivering sound financial results and improving its performance from 2013, our NEOs earned lower
performance stock unit (&#147;PSU&#148;) payouts and significantly below-target annual cash incentive awards because we did not meet our expectations. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Hershey Has Strong Pay-for-Performance Alignment </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Compensation and Executive
Organization Committee (the &#147;Committee&#148;) of our Board of Directors (the &#147;Board&#148;) has responsibility for the oversight of our executive compensation framework and aligning our executive&#146;s pay with the Company&#146;s
performance. We believe we have a strong pay-for-performance alignment because a significant portion of each NEO&#146;s total direct compensation is tied to the financial performance of the Company and shareholder returns. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In 2014, approximately 86% of our CEO&#146;s and 72% of our NEOs&#146; total direct compensation was variable and tied to performance, including a
substantial portion tied to shareholder value. Specifically, 50% of our PSUs were tied to Total Shareholder Return (&#147;TSR&#148;). Combined with the other financial and strategic metrics that determine our NEOs compensation, we have aligned our
executive compensation program with the long-term interests of our stockholders. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">41 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-bottom:0px; "><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Over the last three years, we have delivered a TSR of 79.3%, which is at the 60</FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> percentile of our Financial Peer Group described on page
51.</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center">


<IMG SRC="g791430g34k43.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Our Stockholders Strongly Approve of Our Pay Practices </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Last year, our stockholders overwhelmingly approved our &#147;say-on-pay&#148; resolution, with more than 94% of the votes cast by the holders of Common Stock and more than 99% of the combined votes cast
by the holders of the Common Stock and Class B Common Stock voting in favor. Our approach to executive compensation in 2014 was substantially the same as the approach stockholders approved in 2013. In keeping with the preference expressed by our
stockholders at the 2011 Annual Meeting of Stockholders, our Board has committed to having an annual &#147;say-on-pay&#148; vote as described beginning on page 74. We plan to ask stockholders to express a preference for the frequency of the
&#147;say-on-pay&#148; vote at our 2017 Annual Meeting of Stockholders. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We believe significant reasons for this support are our compensation
and governance policies and practices. These policies and practices include: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Pay for performance.</B> A substantial percentage of each of our NEO&#146;s total target direct compensation is variable, performance-based
compensation. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Performance measures support strategic objectives.</B> The performance measures we use for our variable, performance-based compensation reflect
strategic and operating objectives, creating long-term value for our stockholders. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Appropriate risk-taking.</B> We set achievable performance goals that consider our publicly-announced financial expectations, which we believe will
encourage appropriate risk taking. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>No tax gross-ups.</B> We do not provide tax gross-ups, except for relocation expenses. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>&#147;Double-trigger&#148; benefits in the event of a change in control.</B> In the event of a change in control, the payment of the severance
benefits and the acceleration of vesting of time-based long-term incentive awards granted after April 2011 are &#147;double-trigger&#148; benefits. The severance payments and accelerated vesting of continuing incentive awards will not occur unless
there is also a qualifying termination of employment upon or after the change in control. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>No re-pricings or exchanges of underwater stock options.</B> Our stockholder-approved Equity and Incentive Compensation Plan (&#147;EICP&#148;)
prohibits re-pricing or exchange of underwater stock options without stockholder approval. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">42 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Significant stock ownership guidelines.</B> Our NEOs and other executives are required to accumulate and hold stock equal to a multiple of base
salary. If an executive has not met his or her ownership requirement in a timely manner, the executive is required to retain a portion of shares received under long-term incentive awards until the requirements are met. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Anti-hedging policy.</B> Our NEOs, directors and other insiders are prohibited from entering into hedging transactions related to our stock.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Protective covenants.</B> For the protection of the Company, we require our NEOs to enter into an Employee Confidentiality and Restrictive Covenant
Agreement (&#147;ECRCA&#148;) as a condition of receipt of long-term incentive awards. Failure to comply with the agreement may subject the employee to cancellation of awards and a requirement to repay amounts received from awards.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>The Role and Philosophy of the Committee </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Committee has primary responsibility for making compensation decisions for our NEOs. Additionally, our CEO&#146;s compensation is approved by the independent members of the Board of Directors based on
the recommendations of the Committee. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Committee operates under a charter approved by the Board of Directors. The Committee uses
information from Mercer&nbsp;(US)&nbsp;Inc. (&#147;Mercer&#148;), the Committee&#146;s independent executive compensation consultant, input from our CEO (except for matters regarding his own pay) and assistance from our Human Resources Department to
make decisions and to conduct its annual review of the Company&#146;s executive compensation program. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Committee works with a rolling
agenda. Its heaviest workload occurs during the first quarter of the year, as decisions are made with respect to annual and long-term incentives earned for the prior year&#146;s performance and target-setting and compensation levels are finalized
for the current year&#146;s base salaries and incentive programs. The Committee also reviews and approves this Compensation Discussion &amp; Analysis. During the second and third quarters, the Committee reviews materials relating to peer group
composition, tally sheets, competitive pay analysis and other information that forms the foundation for future decisions. The Committee uses the third and fourth quarters to finalize decisions relating to the peer group and compensation plan design
for use in the upcoming year. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The philosophy of our executive compensation program is to provide a compelling, dynamic, market-based total
compensation program tied to performance and aligned with our stockholders&#146; interests. Our goal is to ensure the Company has the talent it needs to maintain sustained long-term performance for our stockholders, employees and communities. The
guiding principles that help us achieve that goal are: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Recruit and retain. </B>Our program is designed to be market competitive and flexible to recruit and retain top talent for our critical roles.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Pay for performance.</B> A significant portion of our executives&#146; compensation is tied to the performance of our Company, rewarding for both
short-term and long-term progress towards our strategic and operational goals. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Aligned with strategy.</B> Our compensation program is aligned with the strategies of our Company. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Aligned with stockholders.</B> Our compensation program, through both design and payouts, is aligned with the long-term interests of our
stockholders. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">43 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Reinforce robust succession planning.</B> Our compensation program plays a key role in making sure we have the talent we need for long-term success
and to deliver our Company strategies. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Data-driven decision making.</B> We design our executive compensation program and make pay decisions considering a balance of information.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Compensation Advisor Independence </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Under its engagement letter with the Committee, Mercer has acknowledged that the firm is retained by and performs its services for the Committee while working with management to provide advice, counsel
and recommendations that reinforce the Company&#146;s business strategy, economics, organization and management style. Mercer has provided and continues to provide services and products to the Company in addition to its work for the Committee,
including services related to global compensation consulting and surveys for various geographies. Mercer and its affiliates also provide products and services to the Company that are unrelated to compensation, including expatriate consulting
services (provided by Mercer), international benefits consulting and claims processing services (provided by Mercer), brand strategy and design services (provided by Lippincott) and property insurance consulting services (provided by Marsh USA Inc.
and Marsh INSCO LLC). The Committee reviews all fees for services related to executive and director compensation provided by Mercer to the Committee, as well as fees for compensation-related products and services provided to the Company. The
Committee has no role in the engagement of Mercer or Mercer affiliates that provide products or services to the Company that are unrelated to compensation; however, the Committee reviews the fees for such products and services concurrently with its
review of compensation-related fees paid to Mercer. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Fees paid to Mercer and its affiliates for services provided in 2014 related to executive
and director compensation totaled $297,019. Fees paid to Mercer and its affiliates for other services provided in 2014 were as follows: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Committee also received and discussed with Mercer its letter to the Committee addressing factors relevant under the
Securities Exchange Commission (&#147;SEC&#148;) and New York Stock Exchange rules in assessing Mercer&#146;s independence from management and whether Mercer&#146;s work for the Committee has raised any conflicts of interest, as well as
Mercer&#146;s belief that no conflict of interest exists and that it serves as an independent advisor to the Committee. The factors addressed included the extent of any business or personal relationships with any member of the Committee or any
executive officer of the Company; Mercer and its affiliates&#146; provision of other services to the Company; the level of fees received from the Company as a percentage of total revenue of each of Mercer and Mercer&#146;s parent company; the
policies and procedures employed by Mercer to avoid conflicts of interest; and any ownership of Company stock by individuals employed by Mercer to advise the Committee. The Committee considered these factors before selecting or receiving advice from
Mercer, and after considering these and other factors in their totality, no conflicts of interest with respect to Mercer&#146;s advice were identified by the Committee. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In establishing compensation levels and awards for executive officers other than our CEO, the Committee takes into consideration the recommendations of Mercer and the Human Resources Department,
evaluations by our CEO of each officer&#146;s individual performance and Company performance. The Committee evaluates director compensation primarily on the basis of peer group data used for benchmarking director compensation provided by Mercer.
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">44 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Compensation Components </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our executive compensation program includes the key elements as summarized in the following table: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2" COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2" COLOR="#ffffff">Element</FONT></B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2" COLOR="#ffffff"></FONT><FONT

<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Base Salary</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Fixed compensation component. Reviewed annually and adjusted as appropriate.</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Intended to attract and retain executives with proven skills and leadership abilities that will enable us to be successful.</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Each NEO received an increase to their base salary in the beginning of the year consistent with how the Company sets
compensation as described beginning on page&nbsp;46.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#bfbfbf">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Annual Incentive Award</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Variable, performance-based compensation component. Payable based on business results and individual performance.</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Intended to motivate and reward executives for successful execution of strategic priorities.</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Targets as a percentage of base salary were established at the beginning of 2014 for each NEO. No changes were made to the
plan design from the previous year.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Long-Term Incentive Awards</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Variable, performance-based compensation component. Typically granted annually as a combination of PSUs and
stock options. The value of amounts actually earned depend on Company and stock price performance.</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Intended to motivate and reward executives for long-term Company financial performance and enhanced long-term stockholder value by balancing
compensation opportunity and risk, while encouraging sustained performance and retention.</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Targets as a percentage of base salary were established at the beginning of 2014 for each
NEO. The plan design remained consistent with the previous year.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">45 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following charts illustrate the weighting of base salary, annual incentive awards and long-term
incentive awards of target total direct compensation of our CEO and our NEOs: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center">


<IMG SRC="g791430g72n05.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Setting Compensation </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Committee&#146;s annual compensation review for 2014 included an analysis of data, comparing the Company&#146;s executive and director compensation levels against a peer group of publicly-held
consumer products companies that we call the Compensation Peer Group. Mercer provides the Committee with advice, counsel and recommendations with respect to the composition of the peer group and competitive data used for benchmarking our
compensation program. The Committee uses this and other information provided by Mercer to reach an independent recommendation regarding compensation to be paid to our CEO. The Committee&#146;s final recommendation is then given to the independent
directors of our Board for review and final approval. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Companies in the Compensation Peer Group used to benchmark executive and director pay
levels for 2014 were: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="51%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="2%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="47%"></TD></TR>


<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Brown-Forman Corporation</FONT></TD>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-bottom:0px; "><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Committee selected these companies after reviewing publicly-held companies offering
products/services similar to ours, with annual revenues within a range of approximately one-half to two times our annual revenue and market capitalization within a reasonable range of our market capitalization. The 2014 Compensation Peer Group was
composed of companies with annual revenues ranging from $3.8 billion to $18.4 billion (measured as of the most recent fiscal year end) and market capitalization ranging from $1.8 billion to $31.3 billion (measured in the third quarter of 2013).
Hershey&#146;s 2012 annual revenue of $6.6 billion and third-quarter 2013 market capitalization of $20.6 billion were at the 55</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP
STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> and 86</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP
STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> percentiles, respectively. Except for Kraft Foods Group, all of the companies in our 2014 Compensation Peer Group were
included in our 2013 Compensation Peer Group. H. J. Heinz Company and Ralcorp, included in 2013, were not included in the 2014 Compensation Peer Group due to acquisitions occurring in 2013. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">46 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Data from the 2014 Compensation Peer Group was supplemented by composite data from consumer products
companies ranging in size from $4 billion to $15 billion in approximate annual sales. This information was included in three national surveys conducted by Aon Hewitt, Mercer and Towers Watson. The survey composite data provided us with broader,
industry-specific information regarding pay levels at consumer products companies for our NEOs. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-bottom:0px; "><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Committee reviewed a
report summarizing compensation levels at the 25</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">,
50</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> and 75</FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> percentiles of the Compensation Peer Group and the survey composite
data for positions comparable to those held by each of our NEOs. The Committee also reviewed a report comparing the target total cash compensation (base salary plus target annual incentive) and target total direct compensation (base salary plus
target annual incentive plus target long-term incentive) for each of the NEOs against these benchmarks. For retention and competitive considerations, the Company targets each NEO&#146;s total cash compensation and total direct compensation levels
around the 50</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> percentile of the Compensation Peer Group
data or survey composite data applicable to his or her position. The Committee&#146;s final determinations with respect to base salary, target annual incentive compensation and target long-term incentive compensation reflect consideration of the
Company&#146;s and the NEO&#146;s performance, internal comparisons and other factors the Committee deems appropriate. As a result of these factors, the target total cash compensation and target total direct compensation of our NEOs in 2014 was
generally set around the medians. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">During 2014, the Committee received detailed tally sheets prepared by management. Each tally sheet captures
comprehensive compensation, benefits and stock ownership data. The tally sheets provide the Committee with a complete picture of each executive&#146;s current and projected compensation and the amount of each element of compensation or other benefit
the executive would receive in the event of voluntary or involuntary termination, retirement, disability, death, or upon change in control. The Committee considers this information, as well as the benchmark information, when making compensation
decisions. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Base Salary </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Base
salary is the largest fixed component of our executive compensation program and is determined by considering the relative importance of the position, the competitive marketplace and the individual&#146;s performance, responsibilities and experience.
Salary reviews are generally conducted annually at the beginning of the year. Each NEO&#146;s base salary is compared to internal and external references. Base salary adjustments, if any, are made after considering market references, Company
performance against financial goals and individual performance. CEO performance is evaluated by the Committee and independent members of the Board. The CEO evaluates performance of his direct reports, including the NEOs, and reviews his
recommendations for salary adjustments with the Committee prior to their approval of the base salary for each NEO. If a NEO has responsibility for a particular business unit, the business unit&#146;s financial results also will be strongly
considered. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">47 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">On the basis of the foregoing considerations, the Committee, and all independent directors in the case of
our CEO, approved base salaries for 2014 as follows: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">See Column&nbsp;(c) of the Summary Compensation Table on page&nbsp;58 for information regarding the base salary earned by
each of our NEOs during 2014. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Annual Incentives </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our NEOs are eligible to receive an annual cash incentive under the One Hershey Incentive Program (&#147;OHIP&#148;), a program established under our EICP. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The OHIP links the NEO&#146;s payout opportunity to measures he or she can affect most directly. For 2014, our CEO and all employees reporting directly to
him, including the NEOs, had common financial objectives tied to total Company performance consistent with their responsibility to manage the entire Company. Total Company performance targets are established in the context of our announced
expectations for financial performance, prior year results and market conditions. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For 2014, our NEOs were eligible to earn individual OHIP
awards, expressed as a percentage of base salary, contingent upon attainment of Company and individual performance objectives. Each of the NEOs was eligible to receive an OHIP award based on the following target percentages: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:9px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Alfonso</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&nbsp;&nbsp;75</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#bfbfbf">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Ms.&nbsp;Buck</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&nbsp;&nbsp;75</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px">
<P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&nbsp;&nbsp;65</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In determining the target OHIP percentage for each of the NEOs, the Committee, and the independent directors in the case
of our CEO, considered the value of target total cash compensation against market references. For each of the NEOs, in 2014 the target total cash compensation fell in the second and third quartiles of target total cash compensation for comparable
positions. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In general, the final OHIP award is determined by multiplying the NEO&#146;s base salary, the applicable target percentage and
performance scores ranging from 0% to 200% based on Company and individual performance. The Company performance goals are established at the beginning of each year by the Committee. Individual performance goals also are established at that time. If
performance scores exceed the target objectives, a NEO may receive an OHIP payout greater than </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">48 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
his or her target award value. If performance scores are below the target objectives, the NEO&#146;s OHIP payout will be below his or her target award value, subject to no award if performance is
below threshold levels. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For NEOs in 2014, the weighting of Company financial performance metrics accounted for 65% of their target award under
the program. The remaining 35% of their target award was based upon individual performance toward achievement of up to five individual performance goals focused on strategic priorities applicable to the NEO&#146;s position, but tied to the overall
Company&#146;s top priorities for the year. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>2014 OHIP Performance Targets and Results </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The financial performance metrics for our NEOs&#146; OHIP awards reflected our pay-for-performance philosophy. The Company performance objectives for the
2014 OHIP participants centered on the following targets: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For 2014, 65% of the OHIP award for each NEO was based on the Company performance score of 44.69%. The remainder of the OHIP award was determined by
individual performance ratings. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Following the close of 2014, the Committee provided the independent directors with an assessment and scoring
of Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s 2014 performance and achievement relative to his individual performance goals. The individual performance goals for Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey centered on delivery of the Company&#146;s financial goals, strategic leadership and
portfolio and geographic expansion. Based upon the Company&#146;s financial results, growth in key geographies and his leadership, the Committee recommended to the independent directors, and the independent directors agreed, that Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey
earned an individual performance rating of successful. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Tacka, Senior Vice President, Chief Financial Officer, had individual
performance goals that included expanding the Company&#146;s global financial capabilities and designing and implementing a finance approach to support the Company&#146;s strategic plan. The individual performance goals for Mr.&nbsp;Alfonso,
President, International, included business development across geographic regions and leadership of our international businesses. For Ms.&nbsp;Buck, President, North America, the </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">49 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
individual performance goals centered on delivering the North America financial plan, expanding new consumer growth platforms and strategic leadership of our North American businesses. The
individual performance goals for Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day, Senior Vice President, Chief Supply Chain Officer, focused on expanding the international supply capability and capacity, delivering continuous improvement and cost-saving initiatives and driving
supply chain innovation. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey provided the Committee with his assessment and scoring of each NEO&#146;s 2014 performance and
achievement relative to their performance goals. Based upon the results for each of our NEOs, Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey recommended, and the Committee agreed, that each of the NEO&#146;s earned an individual performance rating of successful. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Based upon a 65% weight for the Company financial score of 44.69% of target and a 35% weight for their individual performance scores, our NEOs earned the
following 2014 OHIP awards: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">(1)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Except for Mr.&nbsp;Tacka, target award is based upon actual salary received in 2014; Mr.&nbsp;Tacka&#146;s target award is based upon earnings through
December&nbsp;31, 2014. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The 2014 OHIP payments are included in Column&nbsp;(g) of the 2014 Summary Compensation Table for each
NEO. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Long-Term Incentives </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We provide long-term incentive opportunities to motivate, retain and reward our NEOs for their contributions to multi-year performance in achieving
strategies and improving long-term share value. In February of each year, the Committee awards long-term incentive grants, including PSUs and stock options, to our NEOs. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Committee, and the independent directors in the case of our CEO, determines the value of long-term incentive awards made to each NEO by considering the NEO&#146;s target total direct compensation
against internal and external references. The target award percentages approved in February&nbsp;2014, expressed as a percentage of base salary, were: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">50 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Committee values PSUs using the average of the daily closing prices of the Company&#146;s Common Stock
on the New York Stock Exchange (&#147;NYSE&#148;) in the December preceding the start of the performance cycle. The Committee values stock options using the value of the stock options at the date of grant as determined for financial reporting
purposes (the Black-Scholes value). Overall, after taking into account the long-term incentive awards made in 2014, the target total direct compensation of our NEOs was aligned with the median of total direct compensation for the comparable
positions in the Compensation Peer Group and survey composite data<B>.</B> </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Performance Stock Unit Targets and Results </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">PSUs are granted to NEOs and other executives in a position to affect the Company&#146;s long-term results. At the start of each three-year cycle, a
contingent target number of PSUs is established for each executive. This target is expressed as a percentage of the executive&#146;s base salary and is determined as part of a total compensation package based on the applicable Compensation Peer
Group and survey composite benchmarks. The PSU award generally represents approximately one-half of the recipient&#146;s long-term incentive compensation target award. Dividends are not paid on PSU awards during the three-year performance cycle.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The performance objectives for the 2012-2014 performance cycle awarded in 2012 were based upon the following metrics: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

three-year performance cycle. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Committee selected these metrics to measure performance against internal targets aligned
with our stockholders&#146; interests and investment returns offered by our peer companies. The Committee selected 10 food, beverage and consumer products companies with a median revenue of $8.2&nbsp;billion for use in assessing our Company&#146;s
2012-2014 TSR. We refer to these companies as our Financial Peer Group. The Financial Peer Group is a high-performing group of companies with whom we compete for investors in the food and beverage industry. </FONT></P>

performance cycle at the beginning of the performance year. The annual component allows the Committee to establish performance targets that reflect current business conditions, thus strengthening the link between pay and performance for each year of
the three-year cycle. Payment of any amounts earned, including amounts based on the annual performance goals, will be made in shares of our Common Stock at the conclusion of the three-year performance cycle. The maximum award for any participant in
a performance cycle is 250% of the contingent target award. </FONT></P>
