<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">2014 adjusted earnings per share-diluted. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">At the conclusion of each three-year and annual performance period, the Committee reviews the level of performance achieved and the percentage, if any, of the applicable portion of the target number of
PSUs earned. In determining the final performance cycle score, negative adjustments may be made by the Committee to the Company&#146;s performance score to take into account extraordinary or unusual items occurring during the period. No adjustments
were made in determining the 141.77% performance score or the number of PSUs earned by our NEOs for the 2012-2014 performance cycle. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The
performance metrics and weightings for the 2013-2015 and 2014-2016 performance cycles are the same as the 2012-2014 performance cycle. The actual Company results of $3.98 for the 2014 adjusted earnings per share-diluted reflected a 7% increase from
2013 but did not meet the 2014 target of $4.10. As a result, 3.10% of the final award was earned for this metric in the 2013-2015 and 2014-2016 performance cycles. These PSUs will be paid at the end of each of the applicable three-year performance
cycles to participating executives who are entitled to payouts under the terms of the program. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">See Column&nbsp;(e) of the 2014 Summary
Compensation Table on page 58, Columns&nbsp;(f) through&nbsp;(h) of the 2014 Grants of Plan-Based Awards Table on page&nbsp;60, Columns&nbsp;(i) and&nbsp;(j) of the Outstanding Equity Awards at 2014 Fiscal-Year End Table on page&nbsp;61 and
Columns&nbsp;(d) and&nbsp;(e) of the 2014 Option Exercises and Stock Vested Table on page&nbsp;62 for more information about PSUs awarded to the NEOs. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">52 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Stock Options </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Stock options are an important element of our long-term incentive program, enabling us to align the interests of NEOs with those of stockholders. In general, stock options are awarded annually to the
Company&#146;s executives as well as to other key managerial employees. Stock options entitle the holder to purchase a fixed number of shares of Common Stock at a set price during a specified period of time. The right to exercise the options is
subject to a vesting schedule. Because stock options vest over time and only have value if the price of our Common Stock increases, they encourage efforts to enhance long-term stockholder value. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Committee sets guidelines for the value of stock options to be awarded based on competitive compensation data. The stock option award represents
approximately one-half of the NEO&#146;s long-term incentive compensation target award. In 2014, the target number of stock options awarded to each NEO was determined by multiplying the NEO&#146;s base salary by one-half of his or her target
long-term incentive award percentage divided by the Black-Scholes value of each option on the grant date. The Black-Scholes option-pricing model is described in Note&nbsp;10 to the Consolidated Financial Statements contained in the 2014 Annual
Report on Form 10-K that accompanies this Proxy Statement. The actual number of options awarded may vary from the target level based on each NEO&#146;s individual performance evaluation. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Stock options vest in equal increments over four years and have a 10-year term. As required by the EICP, the options have an exercise price equal to the closing market price of the Common Stock on the
NYSE on the date of the award. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">See Column&nbsp;(f) of the 2014 Summary Compensation Table, Columns&nbsp;(j) through (l)&nbsp;of the 2014
Grants of Plan-Based Awards Table, Columns&nbsp;(b) through (f)&nbsp;of the Outstanding Equity Awards at 2014 Fiscal-Year End Table and Columns&nbsp;(b) and (c)&nbsp;of the 2014 Option Exercises and Stock Vested Table for more information on stock
options awarded to the NEOs. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Restricted Stock Units </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Committee awards Restricted Stock Units (&#147;RSUs&#148;) to NEOs and other executives from time to time as special incentives. RSUs also are awarded by the Committee to replace compensation
forfeited by newly-hired NEOs and by the CEO to employees other than executive officers from the RSU pool described below. In 2014, the Committee did not grant RSU awards to any of the NEOs. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Equity Pools </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">To ensure flexibility in providing awards for recruitment, retention,
performance recognition or in conjunction with a promotion, the Committee is authorized under the EICP to establish a stock option pool, a RSU pool and a separate CEO discretionary equity pool for use by our CEO for such purposes. The pools are
available for approximately 12 months from the date created. The Committee determines whether to establish any or all of these pools annually. Options and RSUs remaining in any pool at the end of the period do not carry over to pools established for
a subsequent period. The CEO may not make discretionary awards from any pool to the NEOs. Stock option and RSU awards from the CEO pools, as well as awards from the CEO discretionary equity pool, are made monthly according to an annually
pre-determined schedule. The exercise price for the options is based on the closing price of our Common Stock on the date of the award. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Perquisites </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Executive perquisites are
kept by the Committee to a minimal level relative to a NEOs total compensation and do not play a significant role in our executive compensation program. The perquisites that we provide, including personal use of Company aircraft, security services
for our CEO, and financial counseling and tax preparation reimbursement, are of the type that we believe </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">53 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
promote the efficiency, effectiveness and focus of our NEOs in the performance of their duties. See the footnotes to Column&nbsp;(i) of the 2014 Summary Compensation Table for information
regarding the perquisites received by our NEOs. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our CEO and the other NEOs are eligible to participate in our Gift Matching Program on the
same basis as other employees, retirees or their spouses. Through the Gift Matching Program, we match contributions made to one or more accredited colleges or universities on a dollar-for-dollar basis up to a maximum aggregate contribution of $5,000
per employee annually. These matching contributions are not considered compensation and are not included in Column&nbsp;(i) of the 2014 Summary Compensation Table. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Retirement Plans </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">NEOs participate in our tax-qualified defined benefit pension plan
(&#147;pension plan&#148;) and tax-qualified defined contribution 401(k) plan (&#147;401(k) plan&#148;) on the same basis as other salaried employees of the Company. Internal Revenue Code (&#147;IRC&#148;) regulations do not permit the Company to
use base salary and other compensation paid above certain limits to determine the benefits earned by the NEOs under tax-qualified plans. The Company maintains a defined benefit Supplemental Executive Retirement Plan (&#147;DB&nbsp;SERP&#148;), a
defined contribution Supplemental Executive Retirement Plan (&#147;DC&nbsp;SERP&#148;), a defined benefit Compensation Limit Replacement Plan (&#147;CLRP&#148;) and a Deferred Compensation Plan to provide these and additional benefits that are
comparable to those offered by our peers. Under the provisions of the Deferred Compensation Plan, our NEOs may elect to defer payments from the DB&nbsp;SERP, DC&nbsp;SERP, CLRP, OHIP, PSU and RSU awards, but not stock options. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The DB&nbsp;SERP was closed to new participants in 2006. No new participants have been or will be added to the DB&nbsp;SERP. NEOs and other senior
executives reporting to the CEO not eligible for the DB&nbsp;SERP are considered by the Committee for participation in the DC&nbsp;SERP. In comparison, the DC&nbsp;SERP typically yields a lower benefit than the DB&nbsp;SERP upon retirement. NEOs
eligible for the Company&#146;s pension plan who are not eligible for the DB SERP, participate in the CLRP. The Company believes that the DB&nbsp;SERP, DC&nbsp;SERP, CLRP and Deferred Compensation Plan help, in the aggregate, to attract and retain
executive talent, as similar plans are often components of the executive compensation programs within our Compensation Peer Group. The DC&nbsp;SERP was established as part of our Deferred Compensation Plan and is not a separate plan. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">See the 2014 Pension Benefits Table and accompanying narrative beginning on page&nbsp;63 and the 2014 Non-Qualified Deferred Compensation Table and
accompanying narrative beginning on page&nbsp;64 for more information regarding the DB&nbsp;SERP, DC&nbsp;SERP, CLRP and other retirement benefits. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Employment Agreements </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We have not entered into employment agreements with any NEO, except
for Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey, our President and CEO. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company entered into an employment agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey in August 2012, which
provides for Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s continued employment as President and CEO and as a member of the Board of Directors. The employment agreement does not have a specified term; Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s employment is on an at-will basis. In the
event Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s employment is terminated by the Company without Cause or he resigns for Good Reason (in each case as defined in the employment agreement), Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey will be entitled to certain severance benefits. In the event of
his termination after a change in control, Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey will be eligible to receive benefits under the Executive Benefits Protection Plan (Group 3A) (&#147;EBPP&nbsp;3A&#148;). He is not entitled to an excise tax gross-up. The employment
agreement subjects Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey to certain non-competition and non-</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">54 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
solicitation covenants under the ECRCA and to compensation recovery (clawback) to the extent required by applicable law and regulations. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">See the discussion beginning on page 66 for information regarding the payments Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey would receive in the event of termination or a change in control. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Severance and Change in Control Plans </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">All of the NEOs are covered by our EBPP&nbsp;3A. The EBPP&nbsp;3A is intended to help us attract and retain executive talent and maintain a stable work
environment in the event of activity that could potentially result in a Change in Control. The severance protection provided under EBPP&nbsp;3A upon a Change in Control is a &#147;double trigger.&#148; The terms of the plan generally provide that a
covered NEO whose employment with the Company terminates in qualifying circumstances within two years after a Change in Control of the Company is entitled to certain severance payments and benefits. The EBPP&nbsp;3A also provides severance benefits
in the event of involuntary termination without Cause unrelated to a Change in Control or voluntary termination for Good Reason within two years after election of a new CEO. Change in Control, Cause and Good Reason are defined in the EBPP&nbsp;3A.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">See the discussion beginning on page&nbsp;66 for information regarding the payments that would be due to our NEOs under that EBPP 3A in the
event of an applicable termination of employment or a Change in Control. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Compensation Policies and Practices </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Clawbacks </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In 2008, the Company initiated
the execution of the ECRCA by executive officers as a condition for the receipt of long-term incentive awards and, for new executive officers, also as a condition of employment. In 2013, the Company expanded the ECRCA to include certain employees
along with executive officers. As is the case with the executive officers, these employees are required to enter into the ECRCA as a condition of the receipt of long-term incentive awards, and, for new employees, also as a condition of employment.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The purpose of the ECRCA is to protect the Company and further align the executive officer with the Company. The terms of the ECRCA prohibit
the executive from misusing or disclosing the Company&#146;s confidential information, competing with the Company in specific categories for a period of 12 months following separation from employment, recruiting or soliciting the Company&#146;s
employees, or disparaging the Company&#146;s reputation in any way. For those officers or employees based outside the U.S., the restrictive covenants and terms may be modified to comply with local laws. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Failure to comply with the provisions of the ECRCA may result in cancellation of the unvested portion of PSU and RSU awards, cancellation of any
unexercised stock options and a requirement for repayment of amounts received from equity awards during the last year of employment, as well as any amounts received from the DB&nbsp;SERP or DC&nbsp;SERP. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Tax Considerations </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The anticipated cost
of the various components of executive compensation is also a factor in the Committee&#146;s deliberations. Section&nbsp;162(m) of the IRC may limit the Company&#146;s ability to deduct certain compensation in excess of $1&nbsp;million paid to our
CEO or to our other NEOs who are employed on the last day of the fiscal year (other than officers who served as CFO during the year). This limitation does not apply to compensation that qualifies as &#147;performance-based&#148; under
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">55 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
applicable Internal Revenue Service (&#147;IRS&#148;) regulations or that is paid after termination of employment. The Committee has considered the effect of Section&nbsp;162(m) of the IRC on the
Company&#146;s executive compensation program. The Committee exercises discretion in setting base salaries, structuring incentive compensation awards and in determining payments in relation to levels of achievement of performance goals. The
Committee believes that the total compensation program for NEOs should be managed in accordance with the objectives outlined in the Company&#146;s compensation philosophy and in the best overall interests of the Company&#146;s stockholders.
Accordingly, compensation paid by the Company may not be deductible because such compensation exceeds the limitations, or does not meet the &#147;performance-based&#148; or other requirements, for deductibility under Section&nbsp;162(m) of the IRC.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC specifies certain rules and limitations regarding the operation of our Deferred Compensation Plan and other
retirement programs. Failure to comply with these rules could subject participants in those plans and programs to additional income tax and interest penalties. We believe our plans and programs comply with Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Stock Ownership Guidelines </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The
Committee believes that requiring NEOs and other executive officers to hold significant amounts of our Common Stock strengthens their alignment with the interest of our stockholders and promotes achievement of long-term business objectives. Our
executive stock ownership policy has been in place for more than 20 years. The Committee reviews ownership requirements annually to ensure they are aligned with external market comparisons. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Executives with stock ownership requirements have five years from their initial election to their position to accumulate and hold the minimum number of shares required. For purposes of this requirement,
&#147;shares&#148; include shares of our Common Stock that are owned by the executive, unvested time-based RSUs, PSUs earned for the annual segments of open performance cycles, as well as vested RSUs and PSUs that have been deferred by the executive
as Common Stock units under our Deferred Compensation Plan. It is anticipated that executives will hold a significant number of the shares earned from PSU and RSU awards and the exercise of stock options to satisfy their obligations. Minimum
stockholding requirements for the CEO and the other NEOs are as follows: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="76%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="58%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="8%"></TD>
<TD></TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#3f000b">
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2" COLOR="#ffffff"></FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2" COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2" COLOR="#ffffff">Position</FONT></B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2" COLOR="#ffffff"></FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2" COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2" COLOR="#ffffff">Stock&nbsp;Ownership&nbsp;Level</FONT></B></FONT></TD></TR>


<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">CEO</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">5&nbsp;times&nbsp;base&nbsp;salary</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#bfbfbf">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">CFO and other NEOs</FONT></P></TD>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The dollar value of shares which must be acquired and held equals a multiple of the individual executive&#146;s base
salary. Stock holding requirements are updated whenever a change in base salary occurs. Failure to reach the minimum within the five-year period results in a notification letter to the executive, with a copy to the CEO, and a requirement that future
stock option exercises and PSU payments be settled by retaining at least 50% of the shares of Common Stock received until the minimum ownership level is attained. The Committee receives an annual summary of each individual executive&#146;s ownership
status to monitor compliance. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As of February&nbsp;27, 2015, the Record Date for the 2015 Annual Meeting of Stockholders, all of the NEOs
exceeded their ownership requirements. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">56 </FONT></P>

Proxy Statement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Submitted by the Compensation and Executive Organization Committee of the Board of Directors: </FONT></P>

2013 and 2012 compensation where required. Because Mr.&nbsp;Tacka was not a NEO in the Company&#146;s 2012 Proxy Statement, the information for his 2012 compensation is not required to be included in the table. </FONT></P>

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">(4)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Column&nbsp;(f)&nbsp;presents the grant date fair value of stock options awarded the NEOs for the years indicated and does not reflect the value of shares actually
received or which may be received in the future with respect to such stock options. The assumptions we made to determine the value of these awards are set forth in Note 10 to the Company&#146;s Consolidated Financial Statements included in our 2014
Annual Report on Form 10-K that accompanies this Proxy Statement. The number of stock options awarded to each NEO during 2014 appears in Column&nbsp;(j) of the 2014 Grants of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Plan-Based</FONT> Awards Table.
</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">(5)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Except for Mr.&nbsp;Tacka, Column (g)&nbsp;reflects the OHIP payments to each NEO based upon actual salary received in 2014; Mr.&nbsp;Tacka&#146;s OHIP payment was
based upon earnings through December&nbsp;31, 2014. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">(6)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Column&nbsp;(h) reflects the aggregate change in the actuarial present value of the NEO&#146;s retirement benefit under the Company&#146;s pension plan, the CLRP, and
the DB&nbsp;SERP. The change in value calculation uses the same discount rate and mortality rate assumptions as the 2013 and 2014 audited financial statements, as applicable, and measures the change in value between the pension plan measurement date
in the 2013 and 2014 audited financial statements. A lower discount rate and the adoption of new mortality tables drove the significant change in value in 2014. The amounts in Column (h)&nbsp;do not reflect amounts paid or that might be paid to the
NEO. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Messrs.&nbsp;Alfonso and O&#146;Day participate in the DC&nbsp;SERP rather than the DB&nbsp;SERP. The DC&nbsp;SERP is established under the Company&#146;s Deferred
Compensation Plan. DC&nbsp;SERP contributions for Messrs.&nbsp;Alfonso and&nbsp;O&#146;Day are included in Column&nbsp;(i) as listed in footnote&nbsp;7 below. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">The NEOs also participate in our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified,</FONT> <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-funded</FONT> Deferred Compensation Plan
under which deferred amounts are credited with notional earnings based on the performance of one or more <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">third-party</FONT> investment options available to all participants in our 401(k) plan. No portion of the
notional earnings credited during 2014 was &#147;above market&#148; or &#147;preferential.&#148; Consequently, no Deferred Compensation Plan earnings are included in amounts reported in Column&nbsp;(h)&nbsp;above. See the 2014 Pension Benefits Table
and the 2014 <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Qualified</FONT> Deferred Compensation Table for more information on the benefits payable under the pension plan, DB&nbsp;SERP, CLRP and Deferred Compensation Plan to the NEOs.
</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">As are all new hires since January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day is eligible to receive a contribution to his 401(k) plan account equal to 3% of base salary
and OHIP up to the maximum amount permitted by the IRS. We call this contribution the Core Retirement Contribution. He also is eligible to receive a Supplemental Core Retirement Contribution equal to the amount by which the Core Retirement
Contribution exceeds the IRS limit. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="line-height:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:1pt solid #000000;width:21%">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">(1)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Column&nbsp;(b) represents the grant date for PSUs reflected in Columns&nbsp;(f),&nbsp;(g)&nbsp;and&nbsp;(h) and the stock options listed in Column&nbsp;(j). All awards
were made in accordance under the Company&#146;s EICP. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">(2)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Columns&nbsp;(c),&nbsp;(d)&nbsp;and&nbsp;(e) represent the threshold, target and maximum potential amounts that each NEO had the opportunity to earn based on the OHIP
targets approved for the NEOs in February&nbsp;2014. Except for Mr.&nbsp;Tacka, all amounts shown in Columns&nbsp;(c),&nbsp;(d) and&nbsp;(e) are based upon actual salary received in 2014. Amounts for Mr.&nbsp;Tacka are based upon earnings through
December&nbsp;31, 2014. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">The threshold amount is the amount that would have been payable had the minimum score been achieved. The target amount is the amount that would have been payable had
the business and individual performance scores been 100% on all metrics. The maximum amount is the amount that would have been payable had the maximum score been achieved on all metrics. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">(3)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Columns&nbsp;(f),&nbsp;(g)&nbsp;and&nbsp;(h) represent the number of threshold, target and maximum potential PSUs for the 2014-2016 performance cycle and for the 2014
adjusted earnings&nbsp;per&nbsp;share-diluted component of the 2013-2015 and the 2012-2014 performance cycles. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Each PSU represents the value of one share of our Common Stock. The number of PSUs earned for the 2014-2016 performance cycle will depend upon achievement against the
metrics explained in the Compensation Discussion &amp; Analysis under &#147;Performance Stock Unit Targets and Results&#148; beginning on page 51. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Payment, if any, will be made in shares of the Company&#146;s Common Stock at the conclusion of the three-year performance cycle. The Committee will approve the targets
for the annual adjusted earnings&nbsp;per&nbsp;share-diluted metrics at the beginning of each of the three years in the performance cycle. The minimum award as shown in Column&nbsp;(f)&nbsp;is the number of shares payable for achievement of the
threshold level of performance on one of the metrics and the maximum award as shown in Column&nbsp;(h) is the number of shares payable for achievement of the maximum level of performance on all metrics. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

worked within the performance periods. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

her 2014 base salary divided by the Black-Scholes value of $21.56 for each option. The Black-Scholes value is based on the $105.96 exercise price for these options determined as the closing price of the Company&#146;s Common Stock on the award date.
The actual number of options awarded varied from the target level based on the executive&#146;s performance evaluation for 2014. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

The actual number of PSUs earned, if any, will be determined at the end of each performance cycle and may be fewer or more than the number reflected in Column&nbsp;(i). As a result of his retirement, Mr.&nbsp;Tacka&#146;s PSU awards will be prorated

<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc791430_26"></A>2014 Pension Benefits Table </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Each of the NEOs, with the exception of Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day, is a participant in our pension plan and is fully vested in his or her benefit under that plan. Messrs.&nbsp;Bilbrey, Tacka and Ms.&nbsp;Buck
are eligible to participate in our non-qualified DB&nbsp;SERP. No benefit is payable under the DB&nbsp;SERP if the executive officer terminates employment prior to age 55 or if he or she does not have five years of service with the Company. As of
December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2014, Messrs.&nbsp;Bilbrey and&nbsp;Tacka had attained age 55 with five years of service and Mr.&nbsp;Tacka elected to retire at the end of 2014. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The combination of the pension and DB&nbsp;SERP plans were designed to provide a benefit upon retirement at or after reaching age 60 based on a joint and survivor annuity equal to 55% of final average
compensation for an executive with 15 or more years of service (reduced pro rata for each year of service under 15). Effective January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, the benefit payable under the DB&nbsp;SERP to an executive who was age 50 or over as of
January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, was reduced by 10%, and the benefit payable to an executive who had not attained age 50 as of January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, was reduced by 20%. The benefit payable to Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey was reduced by 10% and the benefit
payable to Ms.&nbsp;Buck was reduced by 20%. In connection with his promotion to CFO in May 2013, a 2007 arrangement exempting Mr.&nbsp;Tacka&#146;s benefit from the 10% reduction was extended through Mr.&nbsp;Tacka&#146;s retirement. The exemption
had been scheduled to expire in September 2013. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Final average compensation is calculated as the sum of (i)&nbsp;the average of the highest
three calendar years of base salary paid over the last five years of employment with the Company and (ii)&nbsp;the average of the highest three OHIP awards, paid or deferred, for the last five years of employment with the Company. The benefit
accrued under the DB&nbsp;SERP is payable upon retirement (subject to the provisions of Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC) as a lump sum, a life annuity with 50% benefit continuation to the participant&#146;s surviving spouse, or payment may be deferred
in accordance with the provisions of the Company&#146;s Deferred Compensation Plan. The lump sum is equal to the actuarial present value of the joint and survivor pension earned, reduced by the lump sum value of the benefits to be paid under the
pension plan and the value of the executive&#146;s Social Security benefits. If the executive terminates employment after age 55 but before age 60, the benefit is reduced for early retirement at a rate of 5%&nbsp;per year for the period until the
executive would have turned 60. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The CLRP provides eligible participants the defined benefit he or she would have earned under our pension plan
were it not for the legal limitation on compensation used to determine benefits. An executive who is a participant in the DB&nbsp;SERP is not eligible to participate in the CLRP unless he or she (i)&nbsp;ceases to be designated by the Committee as
eligible to participate in the DB&nbsp;SERP prior to his or her termination of employment with the Company or (ii)&nbsp;has his or her employment involuntarily terminated by the Company other than for Cause prior to vesting in the DB&nbsp;SERP. NEOs
meeting these criteria become eligible to participate in the CLRP and receive a benefit for all years in which they would have been a participant of the CLRP had they not been designated by the Committee to be eligible for the DB&nbsp;SERP.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For executives who are eligible for both the DC&nbsp;SERP, as described under 2014 Non-Qualified Deferred Compensation, and the pension plan,
the additional credit under the CLRP is limited to 3% of eligible earnings less the IRS annual limitation on compensation. Mr.&nbsp;Alfonso is the only NEO eligible for the CLRP. Upon separation, benefits under the CLRP are payable in a single lump
sum or may be deferred into the Deferred Compensation Plan. A participant is eligible for </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">63 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
his or her CLRP benefit upon separation from service (subject to the provisions of Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC) after five years of service or attaining age 55 (unless the participant is
terminated for Cause). Payment is also made to the estate of a participant who dies prior to separation from service. Participants who become disabled are 100% vested in their benefit and continue to accrue additional benefits for up to two
additional years. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following table and explanatory footnotes provide information regarding the present value of benefits accrued under the
pension plan, as applicable, and the DB&nbsp;SERP or CLRP for each NEO as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2014. The amounts shown for the DB&nbsp;SERP reflect the reduction for the present value of the benefits under the pension plan and Social Security
benefits. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Mr.
O&#146;Day</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&#151;</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc791430_27"></A>2014 Non-Qualified Deferred Compensation Table </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our NEOs are eligible to participate in the Company&#146;s Deferred Compensation Plan. The Deferred Compensation Plan is a non-qualified, non-funded plan
that permits participants to defer compensation that would otherwise be paid to them currently. The Deferred Compensation Plan is intended to secure the goodwill and loyalty of participants by enabling them to defer compensation when the
participants deem it beneficial to do so and by providing a vehicle for the Company to provide, on a non-qualified basis, contributions that could not be made on the participants&#146; behalf to the 401(k) plan. The Company credits the Deferred
Compensation Plan with a specified percentage of compensation for NEOs participating in the non-qualified DC&nbsp;SERP. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">64 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our NEOs may elect to defer payments to be received from the DB&nbsp;SERP, DC&nbsp;SERP, CLRP, OHIP, PSU and
RSU awards, but not stock options. Amounts deferred are fully vested and are credited to the individual&#146;s account under the Deferred Compensation Plan. Participants elect to receive payment at termination of employment or some other future
date. DB&nbsp;SERP and CLRP payments designated for deferral into the Deferred Compensation Plan are not credited as earned but are credited in full upon the participant&#146;s retirement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Payments are distributed in a lump sum or in annual installments for up to 15 years. All amounts are payable in a lump sum following a Change in Control. All elections and payments under the Deferred
Compensation Plan are subject to compliance with Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC which may limit elections and require a delay in payment of benefits in certain circumstances. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">While deferred, amounts are credited with notional earnings as if they were invested by the participant in one or more investment options offered by the Deferred Compensation Plan. The investment options
under the Deferred Compensation Plan consist of investment in a deferred common stock unit account that we value according to the performance of our Common Stock (for awards paid in stock) or in mutual funds or other investments available to
participants in our 401(k) plan (for awards paid in cash). The participants&#146; accounts under the Deferred Compensation Plan fluctuate daily, depending upon performance of the investment options elected. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Effective January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, we began crediting the deferred compensation accounts of all employees, including the NEOs, with the amount of
employer matching contributions that exceed the limits established by the IRS for contribution to the 401(k) plan. These amounts are credited in the first quarter of the year after they are earned. As shown in the footnotes to the 2014 Summary
Compensation Table beginning on page 58, these amounts are designated as &#147;Supplemental 401(k) Match&#148; and are included as &#147;All Other Compensation&#148; in the year earned. These amounts also are included in Column&nbsp;(c) of the 2014
Non-Qualified Deferred Compensation Table in the year earned. All of the NEOs are fully vested in the Supplemental 401(k) Match credits presented and will be paid at a future date or at termination of employment, as elected by the officer subject to
the provisions of Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Effective January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, we began crediting the deferred compensation accounts of
all employees hired on or after January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, including eligible NEOs, with the amount of Core Retirement Contributions that exceed the limits established by the IRS for contribution to the 401(k) plan. These amounts are credited in the
first quarter of the year after they are earned. As shown in the footnotes to the 2014 Summary Compensation Table, these amounts are designated as &#147;Supplemental Core Retirement Contribution&#148; and are included as &#147;All Other
Compensation&#148; in the year earned. These amounts also are included in Column&nbsp;(c) of the 2014 Non-Qualified Deferred Compensation Table in the year earned. Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day is eligible for a Supplemental Core Retirement Contribution
credit for 2014. Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day is fully vested in this benefit and will receive payment for this benefit at termination of employment subject to the provisions of Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Messrs.&nbsp;Alfonso and&nbsp;O&#146;Day are eligible to participate in our DC&nbsp;SERP, a part of the Deferred Compensation Plan. The DC&nbsp;SERP
provides annual allocations to the Deferred Compensation Plan equal to a percentage of compensation determined by the Committee in its sole discretion. In order to receive the annual DC&nbsp;SERP allocation, an executive officer must (i)&nbsp;defer
in the 401(k) plan the maximum amount allowed by the Company or IRS and (ii)&nbsp;be employed on the last day of the plan year unless the executive officer terminates employment after age 55 and completion of five years of continuous employment
preceding termination, dies or becomes disabled. After completing five years of service with the Company, an executive officer is vested in 10% increments based on his or her age. An executive age&nbsp;46 with five years of service is 10% vested and
an executive age 55 with five years of service is 100% vested. The annual DC&nbsp;SERP allocation </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">65 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
for Messrs. Alfonso and O&#146;Day is equal to 12.5% of base salary and OHIP award for the calendar year, whether paid or deferred. Messrs.&nbsp;Alfonso and&nbsp;O&#146;Day are 100% vested in
their DC&nbsp;SERP benefit. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following table and explanatory footnotes provide information relating to the activity in the Deferred
Compensation Plan accounts of the NEOs during 2014 and the aggregate balance of the accounts as of December&nbsp;31, 2014: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Alfonso&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc791430_28"></A>Potential Payments upon Termination or Change in Control </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We maintain plans covering our NEOs that will require us to provide incremental compensation in the event of termination of employment or a Change in
Control, provided certain conditions are met. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following narrative takes each termination of employment situation &#150; voluntary
resignation, termination for Cause, death, disability, retirement, termination without Cause, and resignation for Good Reason &#150; and a Change in Control of the Company, and it describes the additional amounts, if any, that the Company would pay
or provide to Messrs.&nbsp;Bilbrey, Alfonso, O&#146;Day and Ms.&nbsp;Buck, or their beneficiaries as a result. Information provided with respect to Mr.&nbsp;Tacka reflects his retirement on December&nbsp;31, 2014 at age 61 after 41 years with the
Company. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">66 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The narrative below and the amounts shown reflect certain assumptions we have made in accordance with SEC
rules. We have assumed that the termination of employment or Change in Control occurred on December&nbsp;31, 2014, and that the value of a share of our Common Stock on that day was $103.93, the closing price on the NYSE on
December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2014. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In addition, in keeping with SEC rules, the following narrative and amounts do not include payments and benefits
which are not enhanced by a qualifying termination of employment or Change in Control. These payments and benefits are referred to as &#147;vested benefits&#148; and include: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Benefits accrued under the 401(k) and pension plans; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Vested benefits accrued under the DB&nbsp;SERP, CLRP and account balances held under the Deferred Compensation Plan as previously described on pages 63

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Stock options which have vested and become exercisable prior to termination of employment or Change in Control. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Voluntary Resignation (other than a Resignation for Good Reason) </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We are not obligated to pay amounts over and above the vested benefits to a NEO who voluntarily resigns. Vested stock options may not be exercised after the NEO&#146;s resignation date unless the officer
is age 55 or older and, in certain instances, has met minimum service requirements as described in Treatment of Stock Options upon Retirement, Death or Disability below. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Termination for Cause </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">If we terminate a NEO&#146;s employment for Cause, we are not
obligated to pay the officer any amounts over and above the vested benefits. The NEO&#146;s right to exercise vested options expires upon termination for Cause, and amounts otherwise payable under the DB&nbsp;SERP are subject to forfeiture at the
Company&#146;s discretion. In general, a termination will be for Cause if the executive has been convicted of a felony or has engaged in gross negligence or willful misconduct in the performance of duties, material dishonesty or a material violation
of Company policies, including our Code of Ethical Business Conduct, or bad faith actions in the performance of duties not in the best interests of the Company. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">67 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Death or Disability </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">If an executive officer dies and has not met the vesting requirements to be eligible to receive a benefit from the DB&nbsp;SERP, no benefits are paid. Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey was fully vested in his DB&nbsp;SERP
benefits as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2014. Long-term disability (&#147;LTD&#148;) benefits are generally payable until age 65, but may extend for longer if disability benefits begin after age 60, and are offset by other benefits such as Social
Security. The maximum amount of the monthly LTD payments from all sources, assuming LTD began on December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2014, is set forth in the table below: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">(1)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">For Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey and Ms.&nbsp;Buck, amounts reflects additional lump sum amounts of DB&nbsp;SERP benefit payable at age 65 attributable to vesting and benefit
service credited during the disability period. For Mr.&nbsp;Alfonso, amount reflects two additional years of CLRP and DC SERP credit. For Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day, amount reflects two additional years of Supplemental Core Retirement Contribution and DC
SERP credit vesting upon disability. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Treatment of Stock Options upon Retirement, Death or Disability </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In the event of retirement, death or disability, vested stock options remain exercisable for a period of three or five years but not later than the option
expiration date. The exercise period is based upon the terms and conditions of the individual grant. For awards granted prior to April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, retirement was defined as separation after attainment of age 55. For awards granted on or
after April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, retirement is defined as separation after attainment of age 55 with at least five years of continuous service. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Options awarded prior to April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, that are not vested at the time of retirement, death or disability will be retained and continue to
vest in accordance with the original vesting schedule established on the grant date. Options granted on or after April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, that are not vested at the time of retirement, death or disability will vest in full, and the options will
remain exercisable for three or five years following termination, depending on the terms and conditions of the grant. Options granted in the year of retirement are prorated based upon the number of full calendar months worked in that year.
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">68 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following table provides the number of unvested stock options as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2014 that
would have become vested and remained exercisable during the three-year or five-year periods following death or disability, or retirement, if applicable, on December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2014, and the value of those options based on the excess of the fair
market value of our Common Stock on December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2014, over the option exercise price. Messrs.&nbsp;Bilbrey, Tacka, Alfonso, and O&#146;Day were considered retirement eligible based on the provisions of all option awards on
December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2014. Ms.&nbsp;Buck is not considered retirement eligible because she has not yet reached the age of 55. Ms.&nbsp;Buck would forfeit 116,202 stock options upon voluntary separation. </FONT></P>

<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000" ALIGN="right"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">2,377,389</FONT></TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="line-height:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:1pt solid #000000;width:21%">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">(1)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Represents the total number of unvested options as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2014. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">(2)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Reflects the difference between $103.93, the closing price for our Common Stock on December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2014, and the exercise price for each option.
</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Treatment of RSUs upon Retirement, Death or Disability </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Upon retirement, any unvested RSUs are forfeited. A prorated portion of unvested RSUs granted prior to April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, will vest upon death or disability. The prorated number of RSUs is based
upon the number of full and partial calendar months from the grant date to the date of death or disability divided by the full and partial calendar months from the grant date to the end of the restriction period, multiplied by the number of RSUs
originally granted. Unvested RSUs granted on or after April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, will vest in full upon death or disability. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">None of the NEOs
had RSU awards that would have vested on December&nbsp;31, 2014 if the executive&#146;s employment terminated that day due to death or disability. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Termination without Cause; Resignation for Good Reason </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Under Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s
employment agreement and the EBPP&nbsp;3A, as applicable, we have agreed to pay severance benefits equal to two times base salary plus two times target OHIP award if we terminate the NEO&#146;s active employment without Cause as it is defined in the
applicable document (one and one-half times if the NEO became a participant in the EBPP&nbsp;3A after February&nbsp;22,&nbsp;2011). Each NEO would be entitled to receive a pro rata payment of the OHIP award, if any, earned for the year in which
termination occurs. These benefits also are payable if the NEO resigns from active employment for Good Reason as it is defined in the applicable document. If a NEO&#146;s employment is terminated for reasons other than for Cause, or if the NEO
terminates for Good Reason, the Company will continue health and welfare benefits for a period of two years (18 months if the NEO became a participant in the EBPP&nbsp;3A after February&nbsp;22,&nbsp;2011). </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">If a NEO is under age 55 and his or her employment is terminated for reasons other than for Cause, or if the NEO terminates for Good Reason, he or she
will be eligible to exercise all vested stock options and a prorated portion of his or her unvested stock options held on the date of separation from service for a period of 120 days following separation. If the NEO is age 55 or older
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">69 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
(with five or more years of continuous service with respect to stock options granted on or after April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011) and his or her employment is terminated for reasons other than for
Cause, or if the NEO terminates for Good Reason, the NEO will be entitled to exercise any vested stock options until the earlier of three or five years (based on the provisions of the individual grant) from the date of termination or the expiration
of the options. In addition, if a NEO&#146;s employment is terminated for reasons other than for Cause, or if the NEO terminates for Good Reason, the NEO will receive payment for a prorated portion of any unvested RSUs held on the date of separation
from service. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following table summarizes the incremental amounts that would have been payable to the NEO had his or her employment
terminated on December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2014, under circumstances entitling the NEO to severance benefits as described above: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Reflects the value of unvested options that would vest upon a Change in Control based on the excess, if any, of the value of our Common Stock of $103.93 on
December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2014, over the exercise price for the options. Information regarding unvested options as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2014, can be found in the Outstanding Equity Awards at 2014 Fiscal-Year End Table. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Reflects the full vesting value of DB&nbsp;SERP and more favorable early retirement discount factors as provided under the EBPP&nbsp;3A. Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey is fully
vested in his DB&nbsp;SERP benefit so no additional benefit is applicable. Messrs.&nbsp;Alfonso and O&#146;Day are fully vested in their DC&nbsp;SERP benefit so no additional benefit is applicable. Mr.&nbsp;Alfonso is fully vested in his CLRP
benefit so no additional benefit is applicable. For Ms.&nbsp;Buck, the amount includes the vesting of her DB&nbsp;SERP benefit. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

Section&nbsp;280G if such reduction would result in a greater after-tax benefit for the executive. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Termination without Cause
or Resignation for Good Reason after Change in Control </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">If the NEO&#146;s employment is terminated by the Company without Cause or by the
NEO for Good Reason within two years after a Change in Control, we pay severance benefits under the EBPP 3A to assist the NEO in transitioning to new employment. These severance benefits as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2014, consist of: </FONT></P>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">(4)</FONT></TD>

Mr.&nbsp;Alfonso, the value reflects the amounts of DC&nbsp;SERP, CLRP, 401(k) Match and Supplemental 401(k) Match over a two-year period. For Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day, the value reflects the amounts of DC&nbsp;SERP, Core Retirement Contribution,
Supplemental Core Retirement Contribution, 401(k) Match and Supplemental 401(k) Match that would have been paid had he remained an employee for 12 months after his termination. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">(5)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">For any given executive the total payments made in the event of termination after a Change in Control would be reduced to the &#147;safe harbor&#148; limit under IRC
Section&nbsp;280G if such reduction would result in a greater after-tax benefit for the executive. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">73 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="4"><B><A NAME="toc791430_29"></A>PROPOSAL NO. 3 &#150; APPROVAL OF NAMED EXECUTIVE OFFICER
COMPENSATION ON A NON-BINDING </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="4"><B>ADVISORY BASIS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In accordance with the Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act and related SEC rules, and as required under Section&nbsp;14A of the Exchange Act, we are providing stockholders an
opportunity to approve the compensation of our NEOs as disclosed in this Proxy Statement on a non-binding advisory basis. This proposal, commonly known as the &#147;say-on-pay&#148; vote, will be presented annually until the 2017 Annual Meeting of
Stockholders, at which time stockholders will be asked to vote again on how frequently we should hold the &#147;say-on-pay&#148; vote. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Prior
to submitting your vote, we encourage you to read our Compensation Discussion &amp; Analysis beginning on page 40 and the accompanying executive compensation tables beginning on page 58 for details about our executive compensation program, including
information about the 2014 compensation of our NEOs. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As discussed in more detail in the Compensation Discussion &amp; Analysis, we believe our
executive compensation program is competitive and governed by pay-for-performance principles. We emphasize compensation opportunities that reward results. Our stock ownership requirements and use of stock-based incentives reinforce the alignment of
the interests of our executives with those of our long-term stockholders. In doing so, our executive compensation program supports our strategic objectives and mission. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Accordingly, we ask you to approve the following resolution at the Annual Meeting: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#147;RESOLVED, that the stockholders of The Hershey Company approve, on an advisory basis, the compensation paid to the Company&#146;s
named executive officers, as disclosed in the Proxy Statement for the 2015 Annual Meeting of Stockholders pursuant to the SEC&#146;s compensation disclosure rules, including the Compensation Discussion &amp; Analysis, the Executive Compensation
Tables and the related narrative discussion.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Because your vote is advisory, it will not be binding upon the Board. However, as noted in
the Compensation Discussion &amp; Analysis, the Compensation and Executive Organization Committee and the Board will, as deemed appropriate, take into account the outcome of the vote when considering future decisions affecting executive
compensation. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The affirmative vote of the holders of at least a majority of the shares of Common Stock and Class&nbsp;B Common Stock (voting
together as a class) represented at the Annual Meeting, in person or by proxy, is required to approve this proposal. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">

STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Board of Directors unanimously recommends that stockholders vote <B>FOR</B> approval<BR>of the Company&#146;s named executive officer compensation on a non-binding advisory basis.</FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="4"><B><A NAME="toc791430_30"></A>SECTION 16(a) BENEFICIAL OWNERSHIP REPORTING COMPLIANCE
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Section&nbsp;16(a) of the Exchange Act requires our directors and executive officers, as well as any person who is the beneficial owner of
more than 10% of our outstanding Common Stock, to file reports with the SEC and NYSE showing their ownership and changes in ownership of the Company&#146;s securities. Copies of these reports also must be furnished to us. Based on an examination of
these reports and on written representations provided to us, it is our opinion that all reports for 2014 were timely filed. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="4"><B><A NAME="toc791430_31"></A>CERTAIN TRANSACTIONS AND RELATIONSHIPS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Item&nbsp;404 of SEC Regulation S-K requires that we disclose any transaction or series of similar transactions, or any currently proposed transaction(s), in which (i)&nbsp;the Company was or is to be a
participant, (ii)&nbsp;the amount involved exceeds $120,000 and (iii)&nbsp;any of the following persons had or will have a direct or indirect material interest: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
